Sample Size: 385 respondents

How calculated: Using 95% confidence level with 5% margin of error (standard for research studies)

Distribution across cities:
• Tier-1 cities (Mumbai, Delhi, Bangalore): 200 respondents
• Tier-2 cities (Indore, Pune, Lucknow): 135 respondents  
• Tier-3 cities (Ujjain, Dewas, Ratlam): 50 respondents

Justification: Similar studies on vehicle purchasing behavior in India have used 300-400 respondents. This sample size ensures reliable results for comparative analysis.

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
Primary Data Collection:
• Structured questionnaire with 45 questions (pilot tested with 30 respondents)
• 7-point Likert scales (1=strongly disagree to 7=strongly agree)
• Preference ranking exercises
• Demographic information (age, income, education, occupation)
• Online surveys (Google Forms) and offline paper surveys

Secondary Data Sources:
• Government reports on electric vehicle policies
• Automobile industry association data
• Published academic research papers

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
Analysis Software:
• SPSS software for statistical analysis
• Microsoft Excel for data organization

Statistical Methods:

Basic Analysis:
• Frequency counts and percentages
• Mean, median calculations
• Cross-tabulation tables

Advanced Analysis:
• Chi-square test (to check relationships between variables)
• T-test (to compare two groups)
• ANOVA (to compare multiple groups)
• Regression analysis (to predict preferences)
• Reliability testing (Cronbach's Alpha)

All statistical tests will use 95% confidence level (p < 0.05).

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
Testing Method:

H1: Will use regression analysis to test if environmental concern predicts EV preference

H2: Will use chi-square test to examine relationship between infrastructure confidence and petrol vehicle preference  

H3: Will use ANOVA to compare how different marketing messages affect various demographic groups

Expected Results:
• Statistical significance at 95% confidence level
• Practical significance in real-world application
• Clear evidence supporting or rejecting each hypothesis

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
Research Approach: Two-phase mixed method study

Phase 1 - Survey Research (Months 1-3):
• Distribute questionnaires across three city types
• Target 65% response rate (standard for automotive surveys)
• 70% online surveys, 30% paper-based surveys

Phase 2 - Qualitative Research (Months 4-5):
• 6 focus group discussions (8-10 people per group)
• 15 expert interviews with industry professionals
• Audio recording and transcription of all sessions

Data Integration:
• Compare survey results with interview findings
• Identify common patterns across both data types
• Draw conclusions from combined evidence

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
16. Research Timeline

Month 1-2: Literature review, questionnaire development, pilot testing
Month 3: Ethics approval, participant recruitment, data collection start
Month 4-5: Complete survey data collection from all cities  
Month 6: Conduct focus groups and expert interviews
Month 7-8: Data analysis and thesis writing

Key Milestones:
• Month 2: Pilot study completed
• Month 3: Data collection begins
• Month 5: Target 385 responses achieved
• Month 8: Final submission

